==English==
===Adjective===
{{wikipedia}}
'''non-negative''' (''no [[comparative]] or [[superlative]]'')

#{{mathematics}} Of a [[real number]], either [[positive]] or [[zero]]; not [[negative]]; greater than or equal to zero.
#:''Distances are '''non-negative'''.''
#{{mathematics}} Of a  [[real valued]] [[function]], [[functional]],  ''etc.'' which has non-negative values over a particular [[domain]] ''D''.
#:For all <math> x \in D</math>, <math> f(x)  \ge 0</math>


====Usage notes====
Can be used for an element of a subset of the real numbers, ''eg'' rationals or integers.  This term is '''not''' the same as ''positive''.
====Antonyms====
*[[negative]]<!--Note: "non-positive" is not used, and is NOT an antonym in any case, as it would mean "negative or zero", which is not the mathematical opposite of "positive or zero"-->